author: Al Jazeera English
description:
Palestinians in central Gaza have gathered at the inaugural Gaza International Film Festival for Women’s Cinema to watch Voice of Hind Rajab — an award-winning documentary about six-year-old Hind Rajab, who was killed by Israeli forces last year.
The film portrays Hind’s final moments as she pleaded for help while trapped in her family’s car surrounded by Israeli soldiers.
The screening drew an emotional response from the audience, many of whom said the story mirrored their own suffering.
The film has gained international recognition for its powerful depiction of Gaza’s ongoing tragedy, highlighting the human toll of the conflict through the eyes of a child.
The event also served as a poignant moment of remembrance for Hind and her family.
As Palestinians rebuild their lives amid a fragile ceasefire, the festival stands as a testament to their resilience and determination to reclaim their narratives.

Al Jazeera’s Lina Abu Akleh reports.

Subscribe to our channel: http://bit.ly/AJSubs
title: Gaza’s first women’s film festival screens ‘Voice of Hind Rajab’ in poignant tribute

author: Al Jazeera English
description:
The Israeli military has begun marking the Yellow Line in Gaza as part of its withdrawal plan under a US-brokered ceasefire agreement. 
This marks the first phase of a three-stage retreat, affecting densely populated areas such as Shujayea, Tuffah, and Zeitoun in Gaza City, as well as Beit Lahiya and Beit Hanoon in the north. 
In the south, significant parts of Khan Younis and nearly all of Rafah fall within this demarcation. 
The Yellow Line cuts Palestinians off from vital agricultural land and water resources, while Israel retains control of all crossings, including the Rafah border with Egypt.
Aid agencies have raised concerns over the incomplete or unclear markings, leaving many residents reliant on online maps to view the border's placement.

title: Israel’s ‘yellow line’ explained: What it means for Gaza’s future

description:
Bangladesh’s interim government has unveiled the July Charter, named after last year’s student-led uprising that ousted the prime minister, Sheikh Hasina. 
Critics say it lacks legal weight and clarity, while student groups have refused to sign it, staging protests outside parliament. 
The charter promises term limits and accountability for past abuses, but activists argue it’s merely symbolic without enforcement. 
Many citizens express frustration over weak governance and slow reform. 
Analysts warn the charter risks losing public trust if not backed by concrete action. 
The document highlights Bangladesh’s fragile transition as elections approach.

Al Jazeera’s Tanvir Chowdhury reports from Dhaka.

author: Al Jazeera English
description:
This decisive decade demands unprecedented action to address humanity’s greatest challenge. With global access, this three-part series examines the real consequences of climate change for our civilisation, through the rest of the 21st century and beyond.

Irish journalist Philip Boucher-Hayes visits climate hotspots, from Greenland’s melting glaciers to sub-Saharan Africa’s weather extremes, from the flooding of agricultural land in Bangladesh to the thaw of the Siberian permafrost. He meets experts and witnesses who explain the interconnectivity of the world’s fragile ecology, as we reach tipping points from which there may be no return.

The series looks at new climate science and faces the harsh realities of a changing world - collapsing ecosystems, marine die-offs and escalating extreme weather phenomena. But it also explores a positive vision for reimagining economies, landscapes and infrastructure - and practical solutions, ways of mobilising collective resolve, and challenging

author: Al Jazeera English
description:
Israel’s war has devastated Gaza’s education system, leaving classrooms destroyed and lessons held in tents and makeshift shelters.
Teachers struggle to continue lessons under harsh conditions, with trauma and displacement affecting both learning and focus.
Hundreds of schools have been damaged or flattened, including many run by UNRWA.
Thousands of students and teachers have been killed, injured, or forced to flee their homes.
Psychologists say widespread trauma has severely impacted children’s ability to learn.
Some schools now serve as shelters for displaced families, while others are overcrowded.
Many children remain out of school, still waiting for a chance to resume their education.

Al Jazeera’s Ibrahim al-Khalili reports from Gaza’s Deir el-Balah, Palestine.
UNICEF's Tess Ingram told Al Jazeera that Gaza is the world's most dangerous place for a child. She stressed the ceasefire must now deliver life-saving aid and restore education for 650,000 children, a vital step to avoid
title: No schools left in Gaza: How teachers rebuild education in tents

description:
Israel's bombardment of Gaza may have eased for now, but aid groups say its people are facing severe danger from unexploded ordnance.
The United Nations has warned that clearing it from the Strip could take up to 30 years.

More than 200,000 tonnes of explosives have been dropped on Gaza in two years of relentless Israeli strikes.
About a third of those bombs failed to detonate. That's about 66,000 tonnes of unexploded ordnance scattered across the territory.
At least 53 people have been killed and hundreds injured by the explosives left behind.

Reconstruction in Gaza faces further obstacles from unexploded ordnance. Nicholas Torbet, Middle East director at HALO Trust in the United Kingdom, said Gaza is “essentially one giant city” where every part has been struck by explosives.

Trinidad and Tobago has relations with both countries and is in a difficult position.

Al Jazeera’s Julia Galiano reports from Port of Spain, Trinidad and Tobago.

description:
Easter Island, also known as Rapa Nui, is renowned for its towering stone statues and Polynesian culture. 

But this remote island has endured centuries of formidable challenges - from slavery and disease to the COVID-19 pandemic. 

101 East correspondent Eric Campbell travelled to Rapa Nui to find out how its people have survived against the odds, and why they believe their story offers vital lessons for a more sustainable future.
